{"parse":{"title":"Marathon IV: Road Rogue","pageid":51152417,"revid":812476439,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p><b>Marathon IV: Road Rogue</b> was an eight-day experimental music performance by <a href=\"/wiki/Minneapolis\" title=\"Minneapolis\">Minneapolis</a> musician and composer <a href=\"/wiki/Mark_Mallman\" title=\"Mark Mallman\">Mark Mallman</a>. The project consisted of a continuous, 180-plus hour mobile webcast from the back of a van as it traveled from New York City to Los Angeles. The vehicle was equipped with technology that translated brain waves and heart rhythms into electronic music, allowing the artist to continue performing while he was sleeping.\n</p>\n<div id=\"toc\" class=\"toc\"><input type=\"checkbox\" role=\"button\" id=\"toctogglecheckbox\" class=\"toctogglecheckbox\" style=\"display:none\" /><div class=\"toctitle\" lang=\"en\" dir=\"ltr\"><h2>Contents</h2><span class=\"toctogglespan\"><label class=\"toctogglelabel\" for=\"toctogglecheckbox\"></label></span></div>\n<ul>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-1\"><a href=\"#Origins\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">1</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Origins</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-2\"><a href=\"#Performance\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">2</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Performance</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-3\"><a href=\"#Technology\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">3</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Technology</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-4\"><a href=\"#Objective\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">4</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Objective</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-5\"><a href=\"#References\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">5</span> <span class=\"toctext\">References</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-6\"><a href=\"#External_links\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">6</span> <span class=\"toctext\">External links</span></a></li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Origins\">Origins</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Marathon_IV:_Road_Rogue&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: Origins\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p><a href=\"/wiki/Mark_Mallman\" title=\"Mark Mallman\">Mark Mallman</a> is a Minneapolis piano-based rock musician known for pushing creative and physical limits on stage. Among his most notable performances are a series of \u201cMarathon\u201d events. In 1999, he penned and performed a 26.2 hour song titled \u201cMarathon\u201d at St. Paul\u2019s <a href=\"/wiki/Turf_Club_(venue)\" title=\"Turf Club (venue)\">Turf Club</a>. Five years later he doubled the feat with a 52.4 hour \u201cMarathon 2\u201d performance. And in October 2010 he completed \u201cMarathon 3,\u201d a 78.6-hour song that stretched across four days.\n</p><p>The \u201cMarathon 4\u201d concept emerged from conversations with Stuart DeVaan, a musician and technologist whose company Implex had provided live video streaming services for Marathon 3. DeVaan designed and built the rolling performance space inside a 1992 Vandura conversion van, complete with cameras, mixers, laptops, antennas and a data center to deliver. The duo also partnered with video producer Hamil Griffin-Cassidy and musician Gus Watkins.\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Performance\">Performance</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Marathon_IV:_Road_Rogue&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: Performance\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>The performance began Sept. 15, 2012, in New York City and concluded eight days later in Los Angeles following stops in Pittsburgh, Detroit, Chicago, Omaha, Denver and Las Vegas. The song featured few vocals and consisted of a largely ambient soundscape.<sup id=\"cite_ref-current_1-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-current-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> \u201cSometimes I\u2019m making up lyrics and music and playing live. And then sometimes the machine makes its own music based on instructions.\u201d<sup id=\"cite_ref-star_2-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-star-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> From sunrise to sunset the musicians performed using conventional electronic music instruments, including electric guitar, a Yamaha keytar, iPad apps, a hacked NES cartridge and other gadgets.<sup id=\"cite_ref-wired_3-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-wired-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup> After dark it transitioned to a sleep-mode soundscape generated from the artist\u2019s own biorhythms. \n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Technology\">Technology</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Marathon_IV:_Road_Rogue&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3\" title=\"Edit section: Technology\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>As the sun set, the musician hooked himself up to a Polar heart-rate monitor and a Mattel Mindflex headset, both of which fed into a laptop through an Arduino-based microcontroller kit. Ableton Live sequencing software translated the signals into MIDI messages. One MIDI channel set the song\u2019s tempo based on the heart-rate monitor. Meanwhile, a homebrew program called BioWave turned the brain output into an additional 10 MIDI signals to produce \u201cambient, chordal soundscapes.\u201d The software was developed by a University of Georgia student.<sup id=\"cite_ref-citypages_4-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-citypages-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>During the day, the artist channeled brain waves through a program called Mind Synth using a different neuroheadset called the Emotiv Epoc, sometimes used to control wheelchairs.<sup id=\"cite_ref-wired_3-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-wired-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup> The van was also equipped with five video cameras, mixers, analog-to-digital converters, and a data center containing a video encoding system and two-carrier cellular data system with outboard antennas.<sup id=\"cite_ref-citypages_4-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-citypages-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Objective\">Objective</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Marathon_IV:_Road_Rogue&amp;action=edit&amp;section=4\" title=\"Edit section: Objective\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>Mallman wanted to build on his 78.6 hour \u201cMarathon 3\u201d performance but believed he was reaching the limit of what could be accomplished in a conventional performance and venue. \u201cI had to abandon my body at a certain point, because it was just holding me back.\u201d<sup id=\"cite_ref-current_1-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-current-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> Initially he drew plans for a machine that would move his arms up and down mechanically before moving on to focus on generating sounds from his body\u2019s involuntary systems.<sup id=\"cite_ref-wired_3-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-wired-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup> \u201cFor me, it\u2019s about exploring the back of the mind in music.\u201d<sup id=\"cite_ref-current_1-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-current-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>The artist also sought to abandon the traditional concept of what a venue is. There was no in-person audience beyond the musicians and technicians inside the van, though the performance was broadcast live on the artist\u2019s website, MarkMallman.com.<sup id=\"cite_ref-current_1-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-current-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Marathon_IV:_Road_Rogue&amp;action=edit&amp;section=5\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-current-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\">^ <a href=\"#cite_ref-current_1-0\"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-current_1-1\"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-current_1-2\"><sup><i><b>c</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-current_1-3\"><sup><i><b>d</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation web\">Swensson, Andrea (2012-08-20). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://blog.thecurrent.org/2012/08/mark-mallman-planning-cross-continental-7-day-long-marathon-4/\">\"Mark Mallman planning cross-continental, 7-day-long Marathon 4 &#124; Local Current Blog &#124; The Current from Minnesota Public Radio\"</a>. <i>Blog.thecurrent.org</i><span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">2016-07-24</span></span>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.jtitle=Blog.thecurrent.org&amp;rft.atitle=Mark+Mallman+planning+cross-continental%2C+7-day-long+Marathon+4+%26%23124%3B+Local+Current+Blog+%26%23124%3B+The+Current+from+Minnesota+Public+Radio&amp;rft.date=2012-08-20&amp;rft.aulast=Swensson&amp;rft.aufirst=Andrea&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fblog.thecurrent.org%2F2012%2F08%2Fmark-mallman-planning-cross-continental-7-day-long-marathon-4%2F&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AMarathon+IV%3A+Road+Rogue\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-star-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-star_2-0\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-te